Using the triple product formula, we have
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} \times (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b})) = \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 \|\mathbf{b}\|^2 \cos \theta \sin \theta,\]where $\theta$ is the angle between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$.  Then, using the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, we have
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}\|^2 \le \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 \|\mathbf{b}\|^2,
\end{align*}
so
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}\| \le \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{b}\|.
\end{align*}
Since $\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}\| = 2,$ we have
\begin{align*}
2 \le \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{b}\|.
\end{align*}
Then, for angles $0 < \theta < \pi,$ by the double-angle formula we have
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a}\|^2 \|\mathbf{b}\|^2 \cos \theta \sin \theta &= \|\mathbf{a}\|\|\mathbf{b}\| \cdot \|\mathbf{a}\|\|\mathbf{b}\| \cos \theta \sin \theta \\
&= \|\mathbf{a}\|\|\mathbf{b}\| (\sin 2 \theta) \\
&< \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{b}\| \\
&\le 2.
\end{align*}Moreover, by setting $\theta = \pi / 2,$ we see that this bound is obtained for $\theta = \pi / 2.$  Therefore,
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} \times (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b})) = 2.\)</answer>

